“People just don’t have the expertise or the time.”Target-date funds are supposed to solve those problems.
The fund managers create an asset allocation of stocks, bonds, cash and sometimes real estate or commodities or other investments.
Finally, they change those ratios as you get closer to — or farther into — retirement or taking money out for tuition.
Among the many known failures of the 401(k) experiment is this: In the early years, putting money into a 401(k) was a choice.
Then, the default: Rather than putting people into low-risk investments, channel their savings into target-date funds that correlate with their age.